Banzai51 wrote:ronelson wrote:Quote:Yet he was still branded Kingslayer and had his honor questioned since then.I think his still wearing the white had something to do with that...You would think the ruling or educated class (at least) would put Mad King Aerys + Kingslayer together and realize he did the realm a service. Not like Aerys' madness was any sort of state secret. Yet members of Jamie's own family will spit the epitaph, Kingslayer, at him. And it's not like everyone is pining for Arerys or his rule.Thing is, everyone in the ruling class has their own subjects, guards, household knights, vassals, etc, all of whom have sworn them some sort of loyalty oath, and personal loyalty is the foundation of their society - and every time they see Jaime, they see someone who violated that cardinal rule, and deep down, they can't help but think - what if one of my guards decides the realm is better off without me?Simply put, it wasn't Jaime's place to kill Aerys. Had it been Robert, or Ned, or Tywin, nobody would've flinched - but Jaime, even though he's the son of a great lord, simply didn't rank high enough.
