Quote:Do you disagree that medieval Europe involved a lot of noble houses doing a lot of deals, maneuvering and backstabbing for the attainment of power, and that in this period it mattered less who was "right" than who had the most military/economic/political power?I am not denying that at all. That does not lead me to believe that Martin's world is a realistic portrayal of our world. For instance, the Freys and the Red Wedding. In real life, that would either never have happened, or they'd have paid a heavy price for it. As a race we've shown that we only tolerate traitors when they help us, then we quickly remember that they are traitors and we punish them. There are very few traitors, and none that I can think of on that scale, that were rewarded in the long term for being traitors. It would be more realistic if the Lannisters had hung the elder Frey up and then either confiscating his lands, or hanging the other Freys until they get to one they trust to be their tool. You don't leave an asshole like that in charge where there same thing could happen to you. Not when you're as cold and heartless as the Lannisters.And when you talk about jockeying and backstabbing, how the hell has the eldest Frey stayed in power? That's where I would expect the sniveling weasels to have more effect.That's just my opinion, of course, but the lack of repercussions for the Red Wedding in particularly I have found really bothersome.
